# Shared Across Instances

Static properties and methods belong to the class itself, not to any specific object. They can be accessed without creating an instance, using the `self::` or `ClassName::` syntax.

*   Use the `static` keyword.
*   Inside the class, use `self::` to refer to static members.
*   Outside, use `ClassName::property` or `ClassName::method()`.

```php
class Counter {
    public static $count = 0;

    public static function increment() {
        self::$count++;
    }
}
```

```php
<?php
class MathUtils {
    public static function square($num) {
        return $num * $num;
    }
}

echo MathUtils::square(5); // 25

// Static property example
class Database {
    public static $instanceCount = 0;

    public function __construct() {
        self::$instanceCount++;
    }
}

$db1 = new Database();
$db2 = new Database();
echo Database::$instanceCount; // 2
?>
```
